<subSubSection id="90D39DA9FFECFF87EFA1FCD014F7FCD1" pageId="12" pageNumber="37" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFECFF87EFA1FCD014F7FCD1" blockId="12.[178,1085,843,894]" pageId="12" pageNumber="37">
E t y m o l o g y: The specific epithet is an adjective derived from 
<collectingCountry id="A0DE8EB2FFECFF87EC6CFCD015D6FCCC" box="[895,967,843,864]" name="Myanmar" pageId="12" pageNumber="37">Burma</collectingCountry>
, where this species is currently the sole representative of the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="90D39DA9FFECFF86EFA1FC161751FAC5" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="12" pageNumber="37" type="description">
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFECFF87EFA1FC161477FC71" blockId="12.[178,1085,909,990]" pageId="12" pageNumber="37">D e s c r i p t i o n: Measurements (mm) and ratios: HL: 1.59; HW: 1.53; PW: 1.65; PL: 1.95; EL: 1.37; TiL: 1.40; TaL: 1.16; TL: 11.4; HL/HW: 1.04; HW/PW: 0.93; PL/PW: 1.19; EL/PL: 0.70; TaL/TiL: 0.83.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFECFF87EFA1FC761200FB92" blockId="12.[178,1085,1005,1086]" pageId="12" pageNumber="37">Moderately large species (see measurements). Coloration: head, pronotum, and abdomen black; elytra blackish-brown with a dark-reddish hue; legs dark-brown with reddish tarsi; antennae dark-reddish, with antennomeres I, III, and the apical portion of II blackish.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFECFF87EFA1FBD61731FA9C" blockId="12.[178,1085,1101,1328]" pageId="12" pageNumber="37">
Head (
<figureCitation id="40F2D2A7FFECFF87EFE5FBD61777FBCF" box="[246,358,1101,1123]" captionStart="Figs 15-23" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1503,1525]" captionTargetBox="[191,1085,212,1496]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 15-23: Othius burmensis: (15) head and pronotum; (16) head; (17) median portion of head; (18) sutural portion of right elytron; (19) male sternite IX; (20) aedeagus in ventral view (internal sac fully extruded); (21) lateral internal structures of aedeagus; (22-23) basal internal structure. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 19-20: 0.5 mm; 17-18, 21: 0.2 mm; 22-23: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3985233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3985233/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="37">Figs 15-16</figureCitation>
) weakly oblong, weakly widened posteriorly, and somewhat narrower than pronotum (see ratios HL/HW and HW/PW); anterior pair of frontal punctures distinct, with additional smaller punctures; posterior pair of frontal punctures absent; median dorsal portion impunctate; lateral and posterior dorsal portions with rather sparse and coarse punctures of somewhat variable size; integument with distinct and fine transverse microsculpture (
<figureCitation id="40F2D2A7FFECFF87EED5FB7B1400FB5A" box="[454,529,1248,1270]" captionStart="Figs 15-23" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1503,1525]" captionTargetBox="[191,1085,212,1496]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 15-23: Othius burmensis: (15) head and pronotum; (16) head; (17) median portion of head; (18) sutural portion of right elytron; (19) male sternite IX; (20) aedeagus in ventral view (internal sac fully extruded); (21) lateral internal structures of aedeagus; (22-23) basal internal structure. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 19-20: 0.5 mm; 17-18, 21: 0.2 mm; 22-23: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3985233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3985233/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="37">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
). Eyes of moderate size, approximately half as long as postocular region in dorsal view. Antenna 
<quantity id="1F3163C7FFECFF87ED90FB6614C7FABE" box="[643,726,1277,1298]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="12" pageNumber="37" unit="mm" value="2.9">2.9 mm</quantity>
long; antennomeres V-X weakly transverse.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFECFF87EFA1FADB1731FA66" blockId="12.[178,1085,1344,1482]" pageId="12" pageNumber="37">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="40F2D2A7FFECFF87EE3BFADB1764FAFA" box="[296,373,1344,1366]" captionStart="Figs 15-23" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1503,1525]" captionTargetBox="[191,1085,212,1496]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 15-23: Othius burmensis: (15) head and pronotum; (16) head; (17) median portion of head; (18) sutural portion of right elytron; (19) male sternite IX; (20) aedeagus in ventral view (internal sac fully extruded); (21) lateral internal structures of aedeagus; (22-23) basal internal structure. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 19-20: 0.5 mm; 17-18, 21: 0.2 mm; 22-23: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3985233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3985233/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="37">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) moderately oblong (see ratio PL/PW) and with subparallel lateral margins in dorsal view; discal punctation pattern similar to that of most other East Palaearctic congeners; posterior discal puncture (i. e., puncture near posterior angle) separated from posterior angle by a distance less than its diameter; microsculpture finely transverse.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFECFF87EFA1FA4115EBF986" blockId="12.[178,1085,1498,1579]" pageId="12" pageNumber="37">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="40F2D2A7FFECFF87EFECFA41175BFA5C" box="[255,330,1498,1520]" captionStart="Figs 15-23" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1503,1525]" captionTargetBox="[191,1085,212,1496]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 15-23: Othius burmensis: (15) head and pronotum; (16) head; (17) median portion of head; (18) sutural portion of right elytron; (19) male sternite IX; (20) aedeagus in ventral view (internal sac fully extruded); (21) lateral internal structures of aedeagus; (22-23) basal internal structure. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 19-20: 0.5 mm; 17-18, 21: 0.2 mm; 22-23: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3985233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3985233/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="37">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) shorter than pronotum (see ratio EL/PL); macropunctation rather sparse and shallow; interstices on average several times as broad as diameter of punctures, with very dense micropunctation rendering the surface nearly matt. Hind wings present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFEDFF86EFA1FF401221FEA2" blockId="13.[178,1085,219,270]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Abdomen slightly narrower than elytra; punctation fine and moderately dense; interstices with fine transverse microsculpture; posterior margin of tergite VII with palisade fringe.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFEDFF86EFA1FE85147FFD90" blockId="13.[178,1085,285,572]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">
<specimenCount id="CECF05ABFFEDFF86EFA1FE8516D9FE9F" box="[178,200,286,307]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
: protarsomeres I-IV strongly dilated; sternites V-VII unmodified; sternite VIII posteriorly triangularly depressed, posterior margin weakly concave; posterior processes of hemitergites IX short, apically without tooth-like processes, not reaching posterior margin of tergite X; sternite IX (
<figureCitation id="40F2D2A7FFEDFF86ED12FEEE145DFE20" box="[513,588,373,396]" captionStart="Figs 15-23" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1503,1525]" captionTargetBox="[191,1085,212,1496]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 15-23: Othius burmensis: (15) head and pronotum; (16) head; (17) median portion of head; (18) sutural portion of right elytron; (19) male sternite IX; (20) aedeagus in ventral view (internal sac fully extruded); (21) lateral internal structures of aedeagus; (22-23) basal internal structure. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 19-20: 0.5 mm; 17-18, 21: 0.2 mm; 22-23: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3985233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3985233/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) broad, anteriorly deeply bifid, posterior margin strongly concave, postero-lateral angles without spine-like processes; aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="40F2D2A7FFEDFF86ECFAFE081228FE04" box="[1001,1081,403,425]" captionStart="Figs 15-23" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1503,1525]" captionTargetBox="[191,1085,212,1496]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 15-23: Othius burmensis: (15) head and pronotum; (16) head; (17) median portion of head; (18) sutural portion of right elytron; (19) male sternite IX; (20) aedeagus in ventral view (internal sac fully extruded); (21) lateral internal structures of aedeagus; (22-23) basal internal structure. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 19-20: 0.5 mm; 17-18, 21: 0.2 mm; 22-23: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3985233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3985233/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Figs 20</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="40F2D2A7FFEDFF86EFA1FE2B16FFFE6A" box="[178,238,432,454]" captionStart="Figs 24-29" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1314,1336]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,212,1305]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[178,1085,212,1309]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 24-29: Othius arater (24-26) and O. burmensis (27-29): (24-26) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view; (27-28) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (without extruded internal sac); (29) apical median internal structure of the aedeagus. Scale bars: 27-28: 0.5 mm; 24-26, 29: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3985235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3985235/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">27-28</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity id="1F3163C7FFEDFF86EFEDFE2B175CFE69" box="[254,333,432,453]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" unit="mm" value="1.4">1.4 mm</quantity>
long; parameres apically not distinctly dilated, each with 4 apical setae; internal sac (extruded in 
<typeStatus id="07727080FFEDFF86EEAFFE561407FE4F" box="[444,534,461,483]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">holotype</typeStatus>
) with six sclerotized internal structures: a short and apically weakly curved median basal structure (
<figureCitation id="40F2D2A7FFEDFF86EDB7FE701508FDAD" box="[676,793,491,513]" captionStart="Figs 15-23" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1503,1525]" captionTargetBox="[191,1085,212,1496]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 15-23: Othius burmensis: (15) head and pronotum; (16) head; (17) median portion of head; (18) sutural portion of right elytron; (19) male sternite IX; (20) aedeagus in ventral view (internal sac fully extruded); (21) lateral internal structures of aedeagus; (22-23) basal internal structure. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 19-20: 0.5 mm; 17-18, 21: 0.2 mm; 22-23: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3985233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3985233/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Figs 22-23</figureCitation>
), a distinctly longer median apical structure with a hook-shaped apex (pointing ventrad) (
<figureCitation id="40F2D2A7FFEDFF86EC3CFD93156CFDB2" box="[815,893,520,542]" captionStart="Figs 24-29" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1314,1336]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,212,1305]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[178,1085,212,1309]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 24-29: Othius arater (24-26) and O. burmensis (27-29): (24-26) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view; (27-28) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (without extruded internal sac); (29) apical median internal structure of the aedeagus. Scale bars: 27-28: 0.5 mm; 24-26, 29: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3985235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3985235/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
), and two pairs of long and slender lateral structures (
<figureCitation id="40F2D2A7FFEDFF86ED05FDBE1470FD90" box="[534,609,549,572]" captionStart="Figs 15-23" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1503,1525]" captionTargetBox="[191,1085,212,1496]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 15-23: Othius burmensis: (15) head and pronotum; (16) head; (17) median portion of head; (18) sutural portion of right elytron; (19) male sternite IX; (20) aedeagus in ventral view (internal sac fully extruded); (21) lateral internal structures of aedeagus; (22-23) basal internal structure. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 19-20: 0.5 mm; 17-18, 21: 0.2 mm; 22-23: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3985233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3985233/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFEDFF86EFA1FDC81231FCB5" blockId="13.[178,1085,595,793]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">
C o m p a r a t i v e n o t e s: The similarly modified sculpture of the elytra (dense micropunctation) and the shared absence of a pair of posterior frontal punctures on the head suggests that 
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EE62FD1517E9FD0E" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2018" box="[369,504,653,675]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burmensis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EE62FD1517E9FD0E" box="[369,504,653,675]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. burmensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EDD9FD151575FD0F" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1939" box="[714,868,654,675]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opacipennis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EDD9FD151575FD0F" box="[714,868,654,675]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. opacipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
CAMERON, 1939 and allied species (
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EE5DFD3017FBFD6C" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2003" box="[334,490,683,704]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sericipennis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EE5DFD3017FBFD6C" box="[334,490,683,704]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. sericipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ASSING, 2003; 
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86ED81FD30151EFD6C" box="[658,783,683,704]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. spoliatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="BC58B3D3FFEDFF86EC0BFD3015BBFD6D" author="ASSING V" box="[792,938,683,705]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" pagination="245 - 263" refId="ref8956" refString="ASSING V. (2008): A revision of Othiini. XVI. Four new species of Othius from the Himalaya and China, and additional records (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Staphylininae). - Koleopterologische Rundschau 78: 245 - 263." type="journal article" year="2008">ASSING, 2008</bibRefCitation>
), all of which are distributed in southwestern 
<collectingCountry id="A0DE8EB2FFEDFF86ED10FD53142EFD72" box="[515,575,712,734]" name="China" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="1A0D00C0FFEDFF86ED42FD5314B4FD71" box="[593,677,712,733]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="1A0D00C0FFEDFF86EDA7FD53151BFD72" box="[692,778,712,734]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Sichuan</collectingRegion>
). 
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EC0CFD5315C4FD71" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2018" box="[799,981,712,733]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burmensis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EC0CFD5315C4FD71" box="[799,981,712,733]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Othius burmensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from all of them by a less derived morphology of the aedeagus (less elongate and with the full set of internal structures). In addition, it differs from them as follows:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFEDFF86EFA1FCAB15CBFC17" blockId="13.[178,1085,816,955]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">
from 
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EFE4FCAB178CFCEA" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1939" box="[247,413,816,838]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opacipennis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EFE4FCAB178CFCEA" box="[247,413,816,838]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. opacipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingRegion id="1A0D00C0FFEDFF86EEA4FCAB141AFCE9" box="[439,523,816,837]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="1A0D00C0FFEDFF86ED30FCAB1467FCEA" box="[547,630,816,838]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Sichuan</collectingRegion>
) by distinctly bicoloured antennae (
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EB37FCAB173DFCCF" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1939" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opacipennis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EB37FCAB173DFCCF" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. opacipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: antennae blackish-brown to black), a posteriorly dilated and less oblong head, subparallel lateral margins of the pronotum (
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EDDCFCF0157AFC2C" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1939" box="[719,875,875,896]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opacipennis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EDDCFCF0157AFC2C" box="[719,875,875,896]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. opacipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: pronotum tapering posteriorly), and the shape of the male sternite IX (
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EDCFFC131568FC32" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1939" box="[732,889,904,926]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opacipennis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EDCFFC131568FC32" box="[732,889,904,926]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. opacipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: sternite IX much longer and more slender, anteriorly less deeply bifid, and posteriorly bisinuate);
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFEDFF86EFA1FC4815FAFBEC" blockId="13.[178,1085,979,1089]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">
from 
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EFF8FC481794FC44" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2003" box="[235,389,979,1000]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sericipennis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EFF8FC481794FC44" box="[235,389,979,1000]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. sericipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingRegion id="1A0D00C0FFEDFF86EE87FC4817F9FC44" box="[404,488,979,1000]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="1A0D00C0FFEDFF86EEE0FC481457FC45" box="[499,582,979,1001]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Sichuan</collectingRegion>
) by a posteriorly dilated, much broader, and less oblong head, subparallel lateral margins of the pronotum (
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EC3AFC6B15D6FBAA" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2003" box="[809,967,1008,1030]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sericipennis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EC3AFC6B15D6FBAA" box="[809,967,1008,1030]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. sericipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: pronotum tapering posteriorly), and the shape of the male sternite IX (
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EC36FB9515AEFB8F" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2003" box="[805,959,1038,1059]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sericipennis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EC36FB9515AEFB8F" box="[805,959,1038,1059]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. sericipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: sternite IX much longer, more slender, anteriorly not bifid, and posteriorly weakly concave);
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFEDFF86EFA1FBC31707FAB2" blockId="13.[178,1085,1112,1310]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">
from 
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EFFDFBC3177CFBC1" box="[238,365,1112,1133]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. spoliatus</emphasis>
(
<collectingRegion id="1A0D00C0FFEDFF86EE6DFBC317C0FBC2" box="[382,465,1112,1134]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
) by distinctly bicoloured antennae (
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EC47FBC315C3FBC1" box="[852,978,1112,1133]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. spoliatus</emphasis>
: antennomeres IV-X dark-brown), less transverse preapical antennomeres, a less broad and posteriorly less strongly dilated head, much longer elytra, the presence of hind wings (reduced in 
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EE21FB2B17A1FB69" box="[306,432,1200,1221]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. spoliatus</emphasis>
), the presence of a palisade fringe at the posterior margin of tergite VII (absent in 
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EE87FB551401FB4E" box="[404,528,1229,1251]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. spoliatus</emphasis>
), and the shape of the male sternite IX (
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86ECA9FB551227FB4E" box="[954,1078,1229,1251]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. spoliatus</emphasis>
: sternite IX much longer, more slender, and posteriorly nearly truncate with median excision).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFEDFF86EFA1FAAD1751FAC5" blockId="13.[178,1085,1333,1385]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">
For illustrations of 
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EE64FAAD1400FAE7" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1939" box="[375,529,1334,1355]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opacipennis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EE64FAAD1400FAE7" box="[375,529,1334,1355]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. opacipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86ED0CFAAD14A8FAE7" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2003" box="[543,697,1334,1355]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sericipennis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86ED0CFAAD14A8FAE7" box="[543,697,1334,1355]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. sericipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EDE1FAAD157CFAE6" box="[754,877,1333,1355]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">O. spoliatus</emphasis>
see 
<bibRefCitation id="BC58B3D3FFEDFF86EC8FFAAD1229FAE7" author="ASSING V" box="[924,1080,1333,1355]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" pagination="661 - 691" refId="ref8725" refString="ASSING V. (1999 b): A revision of Othius STEPHENS (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). VIII. Further records, new species, and a new synonym. - Linzer Biologische B eitrage 31 (2): 661 - 691." type="journal article" year="1999">ASSING (1999b</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="BC58B3D3FFEDFF86EFA1FAC816E5FAC5" author="ASSING V" box="[178,244,1363,1385]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" pagination="69 - 88" refId="ref8863" refString="ASSING V. (2003 b): A revision of Othiini. XIII. Horizontal and vertical distribution of Othius, new species, and additional records (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Staphylininae). - Entomological Problems 33 (1 - 2): 69 - 88." type="journal article" year="2003">2003b</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="BC58B3D3FFEDFF86EFEDFAC81724FAC5" author="ASSING V" box="[254,309,1363,1385]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" pagination="245 - 263" refId="ref8956" refString="ASSING V. (2008): A revision of Othiini. XVI. Four new species of Othius from the Himalaya and China, and additional records (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Staphylininae). - Koleopterologische Rundschau 78: 245 - 263." type="journal article" year="2008">2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="90D39DA9FFEDFF86EFA1FA1B17BBFA41" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="D876CE22FFEDFF86EFA1FA1B17BBFA41" blockId="13.[178,1085,1408,1518]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">
D i s t r i b u t i o n a n d n a t u r a l h i s t o r y: 
<taxonomicName id="1FC9B5A1FFEDFF86EC14FA1B15AEFA39" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2018" box="[775,959,1408,1429]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burmensis">
<emphasis id="EABD1230FFEDFF86EC14FA1B15AEFA39" box="[775,959,1408,1429]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Othius burmensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the first representative of the genus to be recorded from 
<collectingCountry id="A0DE8EB2FFEDFF86ED89FA051511FA1F" box="[666,768,1438,1459]" name="Myanmar" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
. The 
<typeStatus id="07727080FFEDFF86EC2BFA051575FA1F" box="[824,868,1438,1459]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">type</typeStatus>
locality is situated in the northeast of the country, not far from the border with the Chinese province Yunnan, at an altitude of 
<quantity id="1F3163C7FFEDFF86EE44FA4317B7FA41" box="[343,422,1496,1518]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.255" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" unit="m" value="2255.0">2255 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
